7.1.12 - M365SR12: Failure of Cloud Service Provider to Report Incidents
ISM controls:
•	Control: 1512; Revision: 3; Updated: Dec-22; Applicability: All; OS: All (Reporting of security incidents by cloud service providers)
•	Control: 0140; Revision: 6; Updated: Jun-21; Applicability: All; OS: All (Reporting security incidents to the relevant authorities)
•	Control: 1506; Revision: 1; Updated: Jun-21; Applicability: All; OS: All (Evaluation of cloud service security)
________________________________________
Current Risk
Microsoft fails to report security incidents or breaches to the agency, resulting in such events going unnoticed, undetected, and un-investigated, subsequently increasing attacker dwell time and the likelihood of malicious activities that carry consequence to agency objectives.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MAJOR	=	MEDIUM
________________________________________
Recommendations:
1.	Mandate Service Level Agreements (SLAs): Ensure that the contract or Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the cloud service provider includes specific, legally binding timelines for the notification of security incidents.
2.	Enable Shared Signal Reporting: Configure Microsoft Entra ID and Defender for Cloud to automatically share security signals and alerts with the agency's Security Operations Centre (SOC) via Graph API or Sentinel.
3.	Perform Independent Monitoring: Implement third-party security monitoring tools that can independently verify the health and security posture of the tenancy, reducing the sole reliance on provider-reported metrics.
- Treatment #1
•	Incident Response Integration: Develop a joint incident response playbook that defines the communication channels and escalation paths between Microsoft Support and the agency’s internal security team.
•	Continuous Telemetry Ingestion: Centralise all M365 audit, sign-in, and security logs into a sovereign SIEM instance to allow for internal proactive threat hunting rather than waiting for provider notifications.
•	Compliance Verification: Conduct an annual review of Microsoft’s SOC 2 Type II reports and Bridge Letters to verify their internal incident reporting effectiveness and adherence to international standards.
________________________________________
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
By formalising notification requirements and establishing independent visibility through log ingestion and proactive hunting, the agency reduces the "blind spot" created by a lack of provider reporting. While a failure to report by the provider still carries a "Major" consequence for the agency, these treatments increase the chance of internal detection, further lowering the likelihood to "Rare."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
RARE	x	MAJOR	=	MEDIUM

